RIP Tony Todd, love of my life (in film). These movies are so silly. After the first one, which was pretty good, all the deaths in these movies are caused purely by easily avoidable human negligence. In the most Road Runner/Wiley Coyote/Acme kind of way. Lol.

Yup, the movie is repetitive (of course, it scared the heck out of me back in the days). But still, we gotta give the devil his due:
1. It has a unique concept: no killer, no ghost, no monster. Just Death, or should I say, a malevolent unseen force known as Death.
2. To be quite frank, this franchise doesn't even need a storyline, or the connection between the installments, at all (luckily, it does). Because this concept can be reused over and over again, as long as the kills are creative (you still have a point, though. Most of the kills are cause by negligence and stupidity). Despite the clichÃ©, they still get me hooked: I'm curious to find out who will go next, and most importantly, HOW.

Anyway, let's wait and see what this one has in store.

First became obsessed with these at a morbidly young age (thank Happy Tree Friends), mostly my fascination with seeing death and destruction in film. Part four is probably my favorite of the bunch for its spectacle (i.e. the race car track and mall premonitions), but I also enjoy parts two and three â€” I have a soft spot for all the other films but itâ€™s my preference. I remember just before part five was released, I saw a fan-made trailer for it â€” which predated the film by two years and accurately predicted the bridge collapse sequence! Only in this case did the fan editor combine snippets from earlier horror films to construct a rough trailer (i.e. The Mothman Prophecies, The Omen remake, The Eye and Premonition) â€“ which look so much better than today's typical digital film processing. As I get older, I can see why I prefer the vintage Y2K-era of films to newer ones.

I hope they make more of these and come up with even crazier ideas â€” maybe a ship disaster, a concert venue / football stadium, ski resort, zoo, aquarium or building collapse? (Well, if you factor in this being about first responders, Iâ€™ll await to see whatever premonitions they can come up with to put a bang on the screen.)Â A wise decision to release this theatrically. (Extreme ğŸ¤“ Warning)

Final Destination 2 established the rule that if new life is brought into the list, then it stops death's plans for that list. This grandma supposedly didn't just have a child, but a whole FAMILY descendant from her. And yet they're saying that death just...waited 20 years before getting bored and trying to kill them? Who knows how many people from the sky tower were still alive when the grandma had her first child, let alone if any were alive at all. Also, if death really was coming for her, how did she survive for so long? Clear, the longest surviving person on death's list to ultimately bite the bullet lasted only a few years I think. And that was in pure isolation in a padded room. A rule established in the SECOND movie should not have been forgotten this easily. I would've expected the life-stealing rule in the 5th movie or the self-skipping rule in the 4th to be forgotten instead. The filmmakers better have a damn good reason to apply a random exception to this. And also, cheap "remember Terry's death?" kill.

TL;DR: this movie's script violates the second movie's rule of death.

Some say this movie is unrealistic and forced. It would be better if it were purely imaginative, as horror should be, with the presence of other entities, especially since this film also gives the main character psychic abilities, rather than forcing it like this.

But they forget that in real life, unwanted things often happen simply due to carelessness, lack of awareness, recklessness, and negligence, leading to negative consequences, whether it's an accident or something else entirely.

And it leaves a mark on the audience's mind, making them paranoid and unconsciously more cautious about everything after watching.

That is what psychological horror is supposed to be.

And that's the core

If the latest theoryâ€”which I firmly believe to be trueâ€”that the five main characters in the Final Destination franchise are the cursed descendants of the people Grandma saved from the collapsing tower is accurate, it should rank among the best writing retcons I have ever seen and make perfect sense. But when you take a moment to reflect and realize one thing, it's completely crazy: if you are cursed by Death in your family tree and you have a premonition of an accident or disaster but save one, two, or more people from it, you have technically "infected" the person you saved to be cursed as well. To put it another way, the "Death curse" is a supernatural virus that, although it is intended to occur when a person dies in a particular accident, does not because of the individual's premonition; or, in other words, the premonition is a proper antibody. To make matters worse, there is a good chance that someone who has been saved by someone with the "Death curse" may spread it to their friends, family, and other acquaintances too.
Holy cow, dude. This is the type of mind-blowing writing Hollywood needs nowadays.

Man, to see Tony Todd so frail is not easy. I lived in LA for 6 months in the late 90s and saw him at a party once. Dude was so physically imposing that it was scary, but i heard him chatting with someone and even with that voice of his, he was kind and respectful. I remember first seeing him in the remake of Night of the Living Dead, and will always remember him mowing down zombies one after another. The Crow, Star Trek Next Gen and DS9, The Rock, and of course the Candyman movies. But my favorite performance of his was in The Man From Earth, a movie about an immortal man who reveals himself to the friends he made over the last 20 years on the night he is going to move on to his next life. Tony Todd is great - the whole cast is, actually, and it is a fantastic script. And his voice work is stellar, of course.

You are missed, big man. RIP.

I think a final Final Destination movie that connects everything would be a perfect way to conclude the series. The franchise has always had a loose connection through William Bludworth and Deathâ€™s rules, but an installment that fully ties together every disaster, survivor, and event would make it feel like one big, horrifying puzzle finally being solved.

Hereâ€™s what Iâ€™d love to see:

-A reveal that the 1960s tower fire survivors were the ancestors of the previous films' survivors, making all the disasters part of one long, generational curse.

-William Bludworthâ€™s true role finally explainedâ€”is he just an observer, or does he know a way to break Deathâ€™s cycle? Maybe he was connected to Esther and the original survivors.

-A final group of survivors from past movies coming together, realizing they were never just random victimsâ€”they were all part of a bigger, predestined event leading to one ultimate confrontation with Death.

-A shocking, mind-blowing endingâ€”either they finally find a way to break Deathâ€™s cycle, or thereâ€™s a dark twist that shows it was all inevitable from the start.

If Bloodlines is setting this up, it could be the franchiseâ€™s way of leading into a huge, epic conclusion. I really hope the filmmakers take the opportunity to give fans something more than just another standalone entry. A true final chapter that brings everything full circle would be legendary.

So when they say "Witness the birth of death" does this mean that this is the very first Final Destination before the previous 5?

@leandrotupas242 yes, this is technically how everything started in the franchise. Everything apparently started with the grandmother when she was young and from there it just trickled down through the generations of the family.

â€‹@@CHRONICLEKAI when we see the book with references to the previous films, that is because when she initially had her premonition she also apparently saw the other family members premonitions as well.

The flashback scenes to the restaurant disaster are supposed to be the first time Death's designs were thwarted.

Chronologically, it looks like the events are going to ordered like:

1960s flashbacks > 5 > 1 > 2 > 3 > 4 > Modern time events ("Bloodlines")
